using ordered logistic regression models and people's security survey data from a 2004 national sample from ukraine this paper argues that different forms of socio economic security significantly increase the readiness of workers to take action if faced with grievances our findings add to the body of literature on mobilization in several ways first they contribute to the social movement literature on post soviet countries by focusing on ukraine they also enrich the social movement literature by the concept of security or the perception of resources across time furthermore our models translate largely macro level concepts such as the political opportunity structure to the microlevel of an individual's attitudes as they relate to their work life finally our results provide limited support for the older grievance theory in the social movement literature grievance is not the most influential factor yet it remains significant download pdf+ complete modified february 2009 pdf no_95_sharkhstephanikova_why_w pdf 432.1 kb topics rule of law and corruption russia ukraine search fsi search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publications of interest ownership transformation economic behavior and political attitudes in russia john s earle richard rose cisac 1996 the pacification of favelas in rio de janeiro why the program is working and what are the lessons for other countries stephanie gimenez stahlberg pdf+ between assertiveness and insecurity russian elite attitudes and the russia georgia crisis gail w lapidus post soviet affairs vol 23 2 2007 pdf+ medical resident inpatient hospice rotation experiences with dying and subsequent changes in attitudes and knowledge a jl hallenbeck merlynn r bergen journal of palliative medicine vol 2 2 1999 cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4581 fax